  "why": "The paper's method, DRFuzz, explicitly identifies 'Fidelity' as a core design criterion, which encompasses both semantic consistency ('preserving original semantics') and naturalness ('looking natural to humans'). The oracle used for detecting regression faults assumes that the ground-truth label of the original seed input is preserved after mutation, making semantic consistency applicable and necessary. To enforce both plausibility dimensions, DRFuzz implements a 'GAN-based fidelity assurance' mechanism. A discriminator is trained on the original, natural dataset to learn the distribution of plausible inputs. During fuzzing, every generated mutant is evaluated by this discriminator, and those that are deemed low-fidelity (i.e., unnatural or semantically inconsistent) are filtered out. Because the discriminator is trained on the original data distribution, it serves as a global check for naturalness and semantic similarity across all fuzzing iterations, rather than just a local check between successive mutants. This design directly prevents cumulative distortion and ensures that generated inputs remain realistic.",
  "evidence": "Page 2, Section I, Fidelity criterion: 'It is important to ensure the fidelity of each fault-triggering test input (i.e., preserving original semantics and looking natural to humans) since such test inputs are more concerned by developers. Indeed, test inputs with low fidelity are easy to fool DL systems, but they are not considered within the scope of the DL systems. To obtain test inputs with high fidelity, DRFuzz designs a GAN-based fidelity assurance method...'\n\nPage 3, Section III-B, GAN-based Fidelity Assurance: 'The Discriminator will be used to assure the fidelity of test inputs generated by DRFuzz, as it considers semantic similarity [1] rather than strict pixel-wise difference.'\n\nPage 4, Section III-B: 'During the fuzzing process, we feed an initial seed into the Discriminator to get a fidelity score, which serves as the fidelity threshold for filtering out the low-fidelity inputs generated from this initial seed.'\n\nPage 9, Section IV.B.2, Contribution of the main component of DRFuzz: 'We further manually evaluate the fidelity of inputs obtained with and without the fidelity assurance mechanism. Specifically, we sample 100 inputs generated by DRFuzz_NG and DRFuzz, respectively, and two authors manually evaluate their fidelity individually... They label 86% of inputs generated by DRFuzz as high-fidelity and only 57.5% of inputs generated by DRFuzz_NG as high-fidelity. This indicates that the GAN-based Fidelity Assurance technique can filter out more than 20% of fault-triggering inputs with low fidelity.'"
